## Standards enforcement

Standards are enforced at three layers — during development via Claude hooks, at commit via pre-commit, and in CI via GitHub Actions.

### Tooling layer (always active)

| What | Tool | When |
|---|---|---|
| Lint + style | ruff | `just lint` / pre-commit / CI |
| Docstrings | ruff `D` rules (Google) | `just docs-check` / CI |
| Complexity | ruff `C90` (max 10) | `just lint` |
| Performance | ruff `PERF` | `just lint` |
| Types | basedpyright `standard` mode | `just type` / pre-commit / CI |
| Test coverage | pytest-cov (≥ 85 %) | `just coverage` / CI |

### Claude commands (on-demand workflows)

| Slash command | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `/review` | Full pre-merge checklist: lint + types + docstrings + test coverage + symbol scan |
| `/coverage` | Run coverage, identify gaps below 85 %, write missing tests |
| `/docs-check` | Audit and repair Google-style docstrings across all source files |
| `/standards` | Consolidated pass/fail report — the "ready to merge?" gate |
| `/release` | Orchestrate a new release: verify CI, bump version, tag, push |
| `/tdd-red` | Validate RED phase: confirm a test fails for the right reason |
| `/tdd-green` | Validate GREEN phase: confirm the test passes with no regressions |
| `/ci-fix` | Autonomous CI fixer: diagnose failures, apply fixes, re-run until green |

### Claude hooks (automatic feedback)

| Hook | Event | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `post-edit-python.sh` | PostToolUse | Runs ruff + basedpyright after every `.py` edit |
| `post-edit-refactor-test-guard.sh` | PostToolUse | Reminds to run tests after multiple `src/` edits |
| `pre-write-src-require-test.sh` | PreToolUse | Blocks writing to `src/` if the matching test file does not exist (strict TDD; optional `pre-write-src-test-reminder.sh` warns instead — register one, not both) |
| `pre-bash-coverage-gate.sh` | PreToolUse | Warns before `git commit` if coverage below 85% |
| `pre-bash-commit-quality.sh` | PreToolUse | Scans staged files for secrets and debug markers |
| `pre-bash-block-no-verify.sh` | PreToolUse | Blocks `git commit --no-verify` |
| `pre-config-protection.sh` | PreToolUse | Blocks weakening ruff/basedpyright config |
| `pre-protect-uv-lock.sh` | PreToolUse | Blocks direct edits to `uv.lock` |

### TDD skills (guided workflows)

| Skill | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `tdd-workflow` | Master orchestrator: guides the full RED → GREEN → REFACTOR → VALIDATE cycle |
| `tdd-test-planner` | Converts requirements into structured test plans with categorised test cases |
| `test-quality-reviewer` | Reviews existing test files for anti-patterns and improvement opportunities |

Load a skill by reading its `SKILL.md`: e.g. `.claude/skills/tdd-workflow/SKILL.md`.

### Definition of done

A feature or fix is **done** when all of the following are true:

1. `just ci` passes with zero errors — runs `fix`, `lint`, `type`, `docs-check`, `test-ci`, and `precommit`, matching the aggregate checks enforced in `.github/workflows/ci.yml` (format/lint, typecheck, pre-commit, and test jobs).
2. Every new public function/class/method has a Google-style docstring (Args/Returns/Raises where applicable).
3. Every new function/method has complete type annotations (parameters + return type).
4. At least one test case covers each new public symbol.
5. `just coverage` reports no module below 85 %.
6. No `TODO` or `FIXME` comments are left in modified files (unless tracked as issues).
7. Logging follows **Mandatory `logging_manager` usage** (below): no `print()`, no `logging.getLogger()`,
   no `structlog.configure()` outside `common/logging_manager.py`.
8. Code outside `common/` prefers imports from `{{ package_name }}.common` over duplicating the same
   behaviour (see **Prefer `src/{{ package_name }}/common/`**).

## Package structure

Source code lives under `src/{{ package_name }}/`.
Tests live under `tests/`.
The `.claude/` directory holds Claude Code slash-command prompts and PostToolUse hooks for local standards enforcement.

### Prefer `src/{{ package_name }}/common/`

Modules under `src/{{ package_name }}/` **outside** `common/` (for example `core.py`, `cli.py`, and
any future subpackages) must **import and reuse** shared code from `{{ package_name }}.common` whenever
it already solves the problem:

| Module | Use it for |
|--------|------------|
| `common.logging_manager` | All logging setup, context, formatted log output, and raw stdout lines for tooling (see **Structured logging**). |
| `common.file_manager` | File / JSON / Markdown helpers instead of ad-hoc `Path` I/O. |
| `common.decorators` | Retries, timing, and other cross-cutting decorators. |
| `common.utils` | Shared small utilities (e.g. slugify) instead of copy-paste. |

If a concern fits `common/` but no helper exists yet, **add it there** (with tests under
`tests/{{ package_name }}/`) and call it from feature code — do not grow parallel utilities inside
`core.py` / `cli.py` / other package paths. **`common/bump_version.py`** is the focused release helper;
the same reuse rule applies to the rest of the tree.

## Code style

- Line length: 100 characters
- Python {{ python_min_version }}+
- Ruff rules: `E`, `F`, `I`, `UP`, `B`, `SIM`, `C4`, `RUF`, `TCH`, `PGH`, `PT`, `ARG`, `D`, `C90`, `PERF`, `T20`.
  Rule `E501` is ignored (handled by the formatter).
  `per-file-ignores`: `tests/**` → `ARG`, `D`, `T20`; `scripts/**` → `T20`.
  `common/bump_version.py` follows the same Google docstring rules as the rest of `src/`.
- **`src/{{ package_name }}/` — no `print()`** — use **structlog** (`structlog.get_logger()`) after
  :func:`{{ package_name }}.common.logging_manager.configure_logging` at the app entry point.
  For a **single raw stdout line** consumed by ``$(...)`` (e.g. `bump_version.py` for releases),
  use :func:`{{ package_name }}.common.logging_manager.write_machine_stdout_line` — never `print()`.
  Prefer helpers in `{{ package_name }}.common` (`logging_manager`, `file_manager`, `utils`, `decorators`)
  instead of ad-hoc I/O.
- Docstring convention: **Google style** (enforced by ruff `D` rules + `pydocstyle.convention = "google"`).
- McCabe complexity: max 10 per function.
- Type annotations required on all public functions and methods (basedpyright `standard` mode).

## Structured logging (structlog)

This project uses **structlog** for all logging. Standard `logging.getLogger()` is never used in
application code.

### Mandatory `logging_manager` usage

All configuration and helpers for logging live in `{{ package_name }}.common.logging_manager`. **You must
use these public APIs** (not reimplement them elsewhere):

| API | When to use |
|-----|-------------|
| `configure_logging()` | **Once** at process entry (`__main__`, Typer callback, ASGI lifespan, etc.) before other package code emits logs. The **only** supported way to attach processors / HUMAN vs LLM mode. |
| `get_logger(name=..., **bind)` | Optional: bound logger name or static fields; may call `configure_logging()` if the app forgot to (library-safe). |
| `bind_context` / `clear_context` | Per-request or per-task fields that should appear on subsequent events. |
| `log_section` / `log_sub_section` / `log_section_divider` | Human-mode section headings (no-op in LLM mode). |
| `log_fields` / `log_message` | Structured or prose messages that respect HUMAN vs LLM formatting rules. |
| `wrap_text` / `list_to_numbered_string` | Text shaping when building content that goes through the logging helpers above. |
| `write_machine_stdout_line` | **Only** when a **single raw line** on stdout must be captured by shell or CI (`$(...)`) — e.g. `bump_version.py` emitting the new PEP 440 version. |

**Event-style logs** (most call sites): after `configure_logging()`, use `structlog.get_logger()` and
`log.info("event_name", key=value, …)` (and `debug` / `warning` / `error` as appropriate).

**Forbidden under `src/{{ package_name }}/` (except inside `logging_manager` itself):**

- `print()`
- `logging.getLogger()`, `logging.basicConfig()`, or other stdlib logging setup
- `structlog.configure(...)` — only `logging_manager.configure_logging()` may configure structlog for this project

### Setup (call once from entry point)

```python
from {{ package_name }}.common.logging_manager import configure_logging
configure_logging()   # auto-detects HUMAN vs LLM mode
```

### Usage in every module

```python
import structlog
log = structlog.get_logger()

log.debug("cache_miss", key="user:42")                              # human only
log.info("order_created", order_id=123, status="pending")           # human only
log.warning("retry_attempted", attempt=2, reason="timeout", llm=True)  # human + LLM
log.error("payment_failed", order_id=123, reason="insufficient_funds", llm=True)
```

### Execution modes

| Mode | Activated by | Log level | Output | Events shown |
|------|-------------|-----------|--------|--------------|
| **HUMAN** | default | `DEBUG` | coloured console | all events |
| **LLM** | `EXECUTION_CONTEXT=llm` | `WARNING` | compact JSON | `llm=True` only |

```bash
# Human development (default)
python -m {{ package_name }}

# LLM agent execution
EXECUTION_CONTEXT=llm python -m {{ package_name }}
```

### Rules — non-negotiable

| ✅ DO | ❌ DO NOT |
|-------|----------|
| `log.info("order_created", order_id=123)` | `print()` anywhere under `src/{{ package_name }}/` |
| `log.info("order_created", order_id=123)` | `log.info(f"Order {id} was created")` |
| snake_case event names | Natural language sentences as events |
| Pass IDs, counts, hashes | Log full payloads or raw objects |
| Flat key-value schema | Nest dicts more than one level |
| `llm=True` for events an LLM agent must see | LLM-relevant events without `llm=True` |
| `bind_context(request_id=...)` at request start | Repeat context keys in every log call |
| Only `logging_manager.configure_logging()` configures structlog / stdlib logging for the app | `structlog.configure()`, `logging.basicConfig()`, or `logging.getLogger()` in application code |

### Context binding

```python
from {{ package_name }}.common.logging_manager import bind_context, clear_context

# At the start of a request/task — all logs in this context get these fields
bind_context(request_id="req-abc", user_id=42)

# At the end — prevents context bleeding to the next task
clear_context()
```

### Preferred event schema

```json
{ "event": "...", "status": "...", "id": "...", "reason": "...", "count": 0 }
```

- Use consistent key names across modules
- Prefer enums / short codes over long text values
- Never log secrets, PII, or full stack traces in LLM mode

### LLM-visible log tagging

Only tag events with `llm=True` when the information is needed for LLM reasoning:

```python
# ✅ Tag: LLM needs to know a payment failed to reason about retry strategy
log.error("payment_failed", order_id=123, reason="timeout", llm=True)

# ❌ Don't tag: internal cache miss — irrelevant to LLM reasoning
log.debug("cache_miss", key="session:abc")
```

### Level guidance

| Level | When to use | LLM-visible? |
|-------|-------------|--------------|
| `DEBUG` | Internal state, never for LLM | Never |
| `INFO` | Normal application events | Only with `llm=True` |
| `WARNING` | Recoverable anomalies worth attention | Only with `llm=True` |
| `ERROR` | Always tag `llm=True` for error events | Yes (with `llm=True`) |

## Markdown file placement rule

Any Markdown (`.md`) file you create as part of a workflow, analysis, or investigation output
**must be written inside the `docs/` folder**.

**Allowed exceptions (may be placed anywhere):**
- `README.md`
- `CLAUDE.md`

Do **not** create free-standing `.md` files (e.g. `ANALYSIS.md`, `NOTES.md`) at the repository
root or inside `src/`, `tests/`, `scripts/`, or any directory outside `docs/`. This rule is
enforced by `.claude/hooks/post-edit-markdown.sh`, which fires after every file write and
surfaces a violation message if the rule is broken.
